Installing¶

pip install <package-name>

not so easy...

  • C extensions
  • Cython
  • Binary dependencies

Procedure:

  1. pip install <package-name>
  2. Compilation error
  3. Seach stackoverflow.com
  4. apt-get install <required-dev-package>
  5. Goto 1

conda install <package-name>

  • Python can be fast enough for data
  • Tools available for mostly everything
  • Easy to install and manage packages

Solutions¶

Overfitting

  • Regularization
  • Cross-validation
  • Simpler models
  • Use more data
  • Ensembles
  • Shrinkage

Imbalanced data

  • Sample weighting
  • Subsampling
  • Custom loss functions
  • Specialized metrics

Non-linear data

  • Non-linear transformation
  • Polynomial features
  • Kernels
  • Non-linear models

Takeaways¶

  • To use supervised learning we need labelled data
  • Building models is easy, but is easy to encounter problems
    • Overfitting
    • Imbalanced datasets
    • Non-linear problems
  • It is usually easier to get good results with trees

How much a picture will be liked?¶

We show a picture 100 times

It is liked 30 times

The empirical probability is 0.30

Classical school¶

Let us understand the pictures, in order to find a mathematical model on how much it will be liked.

Frequentist school¶

Do we have statistical significance to say that at infinity probability will also be 0.30?

Bayesian school¶

Let us model the uncertainty.

In [97]:
import numpy
import scipy.stats
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x = numpy.linspace(0., 1., 1001)
y = scipy.stats.beta.pdf(x, 1, 1)
plt.title('Uncertainty about picture being liked (0 shown, 0 likes)')
plt.xlabel('Probability of picture being liked'); plt.ylabel('Probability of being that probability')
plt.plot(x, y);

  • Use pictures where you're visible, alone, and smiling :)
